  "prompt": "Why was the wax museum in Philadelphia built?",
  "response": "The wax museum in Philadelphia, known as the **Franklin Institute's Wax Museum**, was created to honor **Benjamin Franklin** and his many achievements. It was part of an exhibit designed to educate and inspire visitors by showcasing lifelike wax figures of Franklin and other historical figures. The Franklin Institute, a science museum and educational center, aimed to combine history, science, and art to engage the public in learning about Franklin's contributions to science, innovation, and American history.\n\nThe wax figures were part of a broader effort to make history tangible and accessible, allowing visitors to connect with the past in a visually compelling way. While the wax museum itself is no longer a permanent feature at the Franklin Institute, its creation reflected the museum's mission to celebrate Franklin's legacy and foster curiosity and education.",
